    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Sparks From a Debate, in New York and Beyond</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ken Filmer letter says Rick Lazio flouted rules in debating Hillary Clinton in New York Senate race, and, worse, misquoted Casey Stengel (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lazio and Hillary Clinton Clash on Donations, Taxes and Trust'' (front page, Sept. 14): The Senate, like all government bodies, abides by a strict set of rules. A senator who flouts those rules is unlikely to achieve any success in the Senate. Representative Rick A. Lazio showed an inability to abide by the rules governing his debate with Hillary Rodham Clinton. He produced a ''contract'' and a pen, obviously as props, which are forbidden.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lazio and Hillary Clinton Clash on Donations, Taxes and Trust'' (front page, Sept. 14): The Senate, like all government bodies, abides by a strict set of rules. A senator who flouts those rules is unlikely to achieve any success in the Senate. Representative Rick A. Lazio showed an inability to abide by the rules governing his debate with Hillary Rodham Clinton. He produced a ''contract'' and a pen, obviously as props, which are forbidden.</p>
        <p>Worse, he broke a cardinal rule concerning sacred New York sports heroes: Don't misquote Casey Stengel. Stengel did not say ''You can check it out.'' Every true New York sports fan knows the correct quote: ''You could look it up.'' I suggest that Mr. Lazio look it up in the future.</p>
        <p>KEN FILMER  Staten Island, Sept. 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
